AbstractA predictor—corrector method for solving linear programs from infeasible starting points is analyzed. The method is quadratically convergent and can be combined with Ye's finite termination scheme under very general assumptions. If the starting points are large enough then the algorithm hasO(nL) iteration complexity. If the ratio between feasibility and optimality at the starting points is small enough then the algorithm has O(
$$\sqrt {n L} $$
) iteration complexity. For feasible starting points the algorithm reduces to the Mizuno—Todd—Ye predictor—corrector method.
